# BUISYBOX. List of BusyBox commands

## ![](data:text/xml;base64,)BusyBox

**BusyBox** is a [software suite](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Software_suite) that provides several [Unix utilities](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Unix_commands) in a single [executable file](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Executable_file). It runs in a variety of [POSIX](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/POSIX) environments such as [Linux](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linux), [Android](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Android_%28operating_system%29),and [FreeBSD](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/FreeBSD), although many of the tools iprovides are designed to work with interfaces provided by the Linux kernel. It was specifically created for embedded operating systems with very limited resources. The authors dubbed it "The [Swiss Army knife](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Swiss_Army_knife) of [Embedded Linux](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linux_on_embedded_systems)", as the single executable replaces basic functions of more than 300 common commands. It is released as [free software](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Free_software) under the terms of the [GNU General Public License](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/GNU_General_Public_License), version 2.![](data:text/xml;base64,)

##  Features 

BusyBox can be customized to provide a subset of over two hundred utilities. It can provide most of the utilities specified in the [Single Unix Specification](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Single_Unix_Specification) \(SUS\) plus many others that a user would expect to see on a Linux system. BusyBox uses the [Almquist shell](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Almquist_shell), also known as A Shell, ash and sh.  
As it is a complete bootstrap system, it will further replace the [init daemon](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Init) and [udev](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Udev) \(or the latter-day [systemd](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Systemd)\) using itself to be called as init on startup and mdev at hotplug time.  
The BusyBox Web site provides a full list of the utilities implemented.  


### **Single binary** 

Typical computer programs have a separate [binary](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_file) \([executable](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Executable)\) file for each application. BusyBox is a single binary, which is a conglomerate of many applications, each of which can be accessed by calling the single BusyBox binary with various names \(supported by having a [symbolic link](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symbolic_link) or [hard link](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hard_link) for each different name\) in a specific manner with appropriate arguments.  
BusyBox benefits from the single binary approach, as it reduces the overhead introduced by the executable file format \(typically [ELF](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Executable_and_Linkable_Format)\), and it allows code to be shared between multiple applications without requiring a [library](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Library_%28computing%29). This technique is similar to what is provided by the crunchgen command in [FreeBSD](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/FreeBSD), the difference being that BusyBox provides simplified versions of the utilities \(for example, an ls command without file sorting ability\), while a crunchgen generated sum of all the utilities would offer the fully functional versions.  
Sharing of the common code, along with routines written with size-optimization in mind, can make a BusyBox system use much less storage space than a system built with the corresponding full versions of the utilities replaced by BusyBox. Research that compared [GNU](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/GNU), BusyBox, [asmutils](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asmutils) and [Perl](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perl) implementations of the standard Unix commands showed that in some situations BusyBox may perform faster than other implementations, but not always.

### Examples

Programs included in BusyBox can be run simply by adding their name as an argument to the BusyBox executable:  
`/bin/busybox ls`  
More commonly, the desired command names are linked \(using [hard](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hard_link) or [symbolic](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symbolic_link) links\) to the BusyBox executable; BusyBox reads [argv\[0\]](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Argv) to find the name by which it is called, and runs the appropriate command, for example just  
`/bin/ls`  
after `/bin/ls` is linked to `/bin/busybox.` This works because the first argument passed to a program is the name used for the program call, in this case the argument would be "`/bin/ls`".  
Busybox would see that its "name" is "ls" and act like the "ls" program.

### Appliances and reception

BusyBox is used by several operating systems running on [embedded systems](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Embedded_system) and is an essential component of distributions such as [OpenWrt](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/OpenWrt), [OpenEmbedded](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/OpenEmbedded) \(including the [Yocto Project](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yocto_Project)\) and [Buildroot](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buildroot). The [Sharp Zaurus](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sharp_Zaurus) utilizes BusyBox extensively for ordinary [Unix-like](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unix-like) tasks performed on the system's shell.  
BusyBox is also an essential component of [VMware ESXi](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/VMware_ESXi).  
It is necessary for several root applications on Android and is also preinstalled with some "1 Tap Root" solutions such as [Kingo Root](https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kingo_Root).
